I have spoken about this, but it should often be repeated:

Saying that ancient civilizations were very advanced is completely true; but they were not advanced in a vulgar "progressive" way, like having our current (unnatural) mechanical technologies

Imagining ancient Egyptians having computers, phones, etc. is an incredibly silly and modernist idea that implies having access to artificial tools is inherently good, a pure redditism. They were far more skilled in the more subtle and spiritual ways of life, in the unseen realm

It is idiocy to judge people for engaging in natural activities, I don't think anyone would do this. Obviously, after we introduced them to Christianity, "barbaric" rituals etc. naturally come to an end
Artificial lighting is bad and unhealthy and its use is a sign of a decayed and unnatural society

The idea that Thracians needed a large steel crane, powered by the burning of oil, to stack the megalith rocks one on top of the other, or that Mesopotamians had any use for helicopters, reveals our own inferiority

Many old and rare texts, that were intended to be read only by the few able to understand them, are now publicly available; but their exclusivity is still maintained in our age, by the fact that only those fit for them are the ones to seek and read them

Many races of mankind no longer outwardly exist, destroyed by forgotten genocides and famines, outbred to dilution - but they still live on in others' blood, they still follow their paths, act and manifest themselves in our world. One day they will walk with their own feet again.
